data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3.4+ supports **typed `DynamicData`** using `Tuple` or custom types, eliminating the `object[]` casting:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key differences:**
- Return `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` instead of `IEnumerable<object[]>`
- Use tuples `(...)` instead of arrays `[...]`
- Compile-time type checking — mismatched types are caught at build time, not runtime

This requires **MSTest 3.4+** (Microsoft.Testing.Platform). If you're on an older version, you can alternatively use `[DataRow]` for simple constant cases:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

`DataRow` is simpler but limited to compile-time constants.
